      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" 9780679805960" href="/book/show/236058.There_s_A_Boy_In_The_Girls_Bathroom">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24040859-sarah-adamson?shelf=children-s">children-s</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24040859-sarah-adamson?shelf=elementary-school">elementary-school</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2849127752" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9316868154444418184">This was a tough one. It’s on my daughter’s summer reading list for going into 4th grade. I hadn’t read it so checked it out from the library.<br/>I anticipated it being about a transgender kid until I noticed the publication date. And then I was disappointed. I wanted the book to be dealing with a current real issue. <br/>I forced myself to read it.<br/><br/>Wow.<br/><br/>I’m not actually sure where to start.<br/>It started as the sort of book I don’t really like - there are mean kids and bad kids and some of them are full of to</span>
  <span id="freeText9316868154444418184" style="display:none">This was a tough one. It’s on my daughter’s summer reading list for going into 4th grade. I hadn’t read it so checked it out from the library.<br />I anticipated it being about a transgender kid until I noticed the publication date. And then I was disappointed. I wanted the book to be dealing with a current real issue. <br />I forced myself to read it.<br /><br />Wow.<br /><br />I’m not actually sure where to start.<br />It started as the sort of book I don’t really like - there are mean kids and bad kids and some of them are full of toilet humor and some are lovey-dovey seeing romance everywhere.<br /><br />Then Carla, the counselor entered the book. <br />Immediately this book changed from a classic school story about kids being the worst sort of kids to being a book about real kids, poking at each other and themselves to learn - about themselves and what they really wanted and like in life, about their friends and not-so friends to give them a chance to explore and learn who they are.<br /><br />This book gave me the best child psychology lessons I’ve had since medical school! <br /><br />Bradley is the brat, the kid who got held back by a year but is physically bigger and yet emotionally more immature. Jeff is the new kid who just wants to fit in. Carla is the new counselor, who comes with no agenda, no right answers, but is a guide to be there for whatever the kids need and to direct them to find their paths by themselves instead of giving them all the correct answers. <br /><br />I want Carla in my daughter’s life. I desperately want her in our school. <br /><br />Incredibly well written. <br /><br />I will read this with my daughter because I’m not sure she will get past the first school nonsense part to realize just how awesome this book is.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9316868154444418184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


